Rstudio workflow

Manuel Villarreal

2024-08-27

  • Create a directory for the class, you can organize that directory however you want but its always better to have things in the same place.

  • Open Rstudio and create a project inside the directory you just created. To create a new project:

    1. Go to file and click create a new project.

    2. Then click on the Existing Directory option.

    3. On the new window click the browse option and select the directory you created in step one.

Projects allow us to organize our work and bypass the problem of setting a working directory every time we start working with a new data set.

Here is an example of a project organization:

When you open a project in RStudio, it automatically sets up the working directory to the root directory of the project.

Now its your turn.

  1. Create a new directory named extra in your class directory.

  2. Create a new directory named data in the extra folder.

  3. Download the file example.csv located in the R/RStudio module on canvas, and then save that file to the data directory you created.

  4. Open RStudio and start a new R markdown file.

  5. Using a code chunk load the data into the environment (if your not sure how check the cheat-sheet rmarkdown.pdf)

  6. Calculate the mean and standard deviation of the two variables in the data set and print them using the inline code function.

  7. Draw a histogram of both variables (you can use base R or ggplot2, check the data-visualization.pdf cheat-sheet if you want to know how to do it in ggplot2).

  8. Draw a scatter plot of x vs y.
